english:
  title: Letter to Chancellor Xiao Gou upon His Appointment to the Chancellery and Historiography Office
  author: Choe Chiwon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Yesterday I glimpsed the imperial decree and beheld your lofty words and grand designs ascending to the Central Ministry, while simultaneously achieving the honor of the Historiography Office—truly fulfilling the aspirations of our scholarly tradition.

    I venture to reflect that the records of state hold great weight, yet the brush that shapes them bears greater burden. To establish the standards of an entire age, to eclipse the methods of a hundred kings—such is the work that requires the Emperor's most discerning eye, commanding the reverence of all officials at court. How much more so when speaking of you, the Chancellor—a true gentleman-scholar embodying the virtue of one seasoned in wisdom. You harmonize the hundred offices and assist in the ten thousand affairs of state.

    Now that the nation's affairs flourish and our laws find order, the highest positions of East and West Ministries are filled without gap or flaw, and the upright words of left and right historians bear fruit in proper measure. How your achievements illuminate virtue! Like the ancients who sealed their words in silence, you now wield the pen to mend the torn robes of state, displaying the transformation that comes from benevolent rule. Surely you will exalt truth while exposing falsehood, clarifying the three principles of historical record, while suppressing corruption and elevating clarity, inspiring all to serve the throne with undivided hearts. Such is the excellence of ages past and present, inspiring awe from far and near.

    I, dwelling in distant borderlands, have merely benefited from such cultivation, ever mindful of the six principles of governance, dare only to hope for the grace of a single word of commendation. My joy overflows, yet words fail to convey it. I humbly await your benevolent consideration.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'six principles' (六條) likely refers to the six ministerial offices or fundamental principles of governance in classical Chinese administration.
  - key: ''
    value: The metaphor of 'mending the torn robes' (補袞) refers to the chancellor's role in assisting and correcting the emperor's governance.
  - key: ''
    value: '''Sealing words in silence'' alludes to the legendary historiographers You and Xia who refused to compromise their records even under threat.'
